In article <BvExML.Juq@usenet.ucs.indiana.edu> shulick@yankton.ucs.indiana.edu writes:
>Let's say someone retreives the DES source code, which is easy enough.  Why
>WOULDN'T they be able to take every single mathematical operation, reverse each
>one, and then have a "decrypt()"?

It's been done.  In fact, it will probably come with the DES
source.  It may even be called "decrypt()"!  Problem is, it requires
a key...

DES is entirely reversible if you have the key, but not very
reversible otherwise; it would be a rather useless system otherwise.

>Sam Hulick

